{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489738"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:28:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:28:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"731"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/731"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.64,0.06,0.12,0.06,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"731"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114588"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"731","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/731"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"731"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96591"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"390"},{"type":"tags","id":"2098"},{"type":"tags","id":"2115"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"},{"type":"tags","id":"8218"},{"type":"tags","id":"8222"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5315"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5318"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11596"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14293"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114588"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman has recently undergone a total thyroidectomy for a symptomatic multinodular goitre. In addition to multiple benign nodules, the pathologist reported the incidental finding of a 1 cm papillary thyroid carcinoma within the left lobe of the thyroid gland, which was clear of the surgical margins, and no features of aggressive histology. The patient was discharged on thyroxine replacement.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management of the patient\u2019s papillary thyroid carcinoma?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Biannual GP follow up with neck ultrasound in 12 months","Monthly neck examinations for the first year","Radioactive iodine treatment","Whole body iodine scan in six months","Six monthly Tg and TgAb levels"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESurgery is the ideal management for thyroid carcinoma, with the most common procedure being the total thyroidectomy. Fortunately, in this case the patient has undergone this method for management of her goitre and hence the first step in her carcinoma management has been completed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk-stratification is an essential part of determining long-term follow up following surgical treatment of papillary thyroid carcinoma. The American Thyroid Association (ATA) defines \u201clow risk\u201d papillary thyroid carcinoma as having the following characteristics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Intrathyroidal tumour \u0026lt;4cm in size, with absence of gross extrathyroidal extension/vascular invasion/aggressive histology subtypes\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Complete macroscopy tumour resection\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E3.\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 No macroscopic locoregional or distant metastases\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven this patient\u2019s papillary thyroid carcinoma is 1 cm in size, has been resected with clear surgical margins, and has no features of aggressive histology, it is categorised as low risk. The American Thyroid Association\u2019s recommended management for low risk papillary thyroid carcinoma is\u00a0biannual GP review for two years, then annually, as well as 12-24 monthly neck ultrasonography. As such, \u003Cstrong\u003EBiannual GP follow up with neck ultrasound in 12 months \u003C/strong\u003Eis the most appropriate plan of management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECompletion of a total thyroidectomy also allows for the ability to complete adjuvant\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Eradioactive iodine treatment (RAI)\u003C/strong\u003E. This used to be administered in majority of patients post-thyroidectomy for papillary thyroid carcinoma, however now a risk of recurrence classification is used to guide management. Risk of recurrence is categorised as low, medium and high, with some intermediate risk and most high risk malignancies managed with RAI. Those at an intermediate or high risk should have these investigations\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Ereviewed every six months\u003C/strong\u003E, with a\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Ewhole body iodine scan yearly\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonthly neck examinations for the first year\u003C/strong\u003E is overly frequent and unnecessary and is not recommended by the American Thyroid Association as a means of follow up following thyroidectomy for papillary thyroid carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESix monthly Tg and TgAb levels \u003C/strong\u003Eis not the most appropriate answer, as this patient has low risk papillary thyroid carcinoma. 6 - 12 monthly Tg and TgAB is recommended in high risk patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Management of papillary thyroid carcinoma is guided by the risk of recurrence."],"references":["Perri F, Giordano A, Pisconti S, Ionna F, Chiofalo MG, Longo F, et al. Thyroid cancer management: from a suspicious nodule to targeted therapy. Anti-cancer drugs. 2018;29(6):483\u201390. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29649016/","Mallick UK, Harmer C. Practical Management of Thyroid Cancer A Multidisciplinary Approach. 2nd ed. 2018. Cham: Springer International Publishing; 2018. Available at: https://link.springer.com/book/10.1007/978-3-319-91725-2","Watson-Brown P, Anderson D. Differentiated thyroid cancer AJGP Vol. 52, No. 1\u20132, Jan\u2013Feb 2023 https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2023/january-february/differentiated-thyroid-cancer","Fields TD, Underwood HJ, Pitt SC. Management of Small Papillary Thyroid Cancers. Surg Clin N Am 104; 2024:725\u201340 https://doi.org/10.1016/j.suc.2024.02.003"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96591"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"731"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96591"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-17T20:59:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-17T20:59:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"731"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114588"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"ty